A quick overview of the data points suggests that there is an issue with our weight column.

class(mass_data$weight) #determine the data class in the weight column
## [1] "character"


The weight column is made up of character values.

non_numeric_values <- mass_data[grep("[^0-9.]", mass_data$weight), ] #return data that is non-numeric in weight column
non_numeric_values #xkg entries in weight column make it character values
## # A tibble: 2 × 8
##      ID   age sex   n_babies  site  year pop_size weight
##   <dbl> <dbl> <chr>    <dbl> <dbl> <dbl>    <dbl> <chr> 
## 1   166     6 f            2     3  1986      131 2kg   
## 2   354     0 m            2     2  2008      147 5kg


These values must be numeric.

mass_data$weight[mass_data$weight == ("2kg")] <- "2.00"  #change 2kg 
mass_data$weight[mass_data$weight == ("5kg")] <- "5.00" #change 5kg
mass_data$weight <- as.numeric(mass_data$weight) #turn character values into numeric
class(mass_data$weight) #check the data class 
## [1] "numeric"

Testing different distributions of GLM

mod_gamma <- glm(weight ~ age + sex + year + mean_NAO + site + year:mean_NAO, data = mass_NAO_data, family = Gamma(link = "log")) #gamma model with log link
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(mod_gamma)

summary(mod_gamma) #deescriptive statistsics of model

#fit a gamma distribution
gammafit <- fitdist(mass_NAO_data$weight, "gamma")

#FIT ESTIMATES
shape <- gammafit$estimate["shape"]
rate <- gammafit$estimate["rate"]

#generate quantiles from the gamma distribution
theoretical_quantiles <- qgamma(ppoints(length(mass_NAO_data$weight)), shape = shape, rate = rate)

#create qqplot
qqplot(theoretical_quantiles, mass_NAO_data$weight, main = "Q-Q Plot against Gamma Distribution")
abline(0, 1, col = "red", lwd = 2)  #reference line

Determining predictors and fitting a GLM

Next, we create a model with all variables with regards to weight, to determine which have a significant effect and are therefore predictor variables.

predictormodel <- lm(weight ~ age +
                       ID +
                       sex +
                       n_babies +
                       site +
                       year + 
                       pop_size +
                       mean_NAO +
                       year:mean_NAO,
                     data = cleaned_data) #include all variables

Our GLM with site is marginally better as shown by the AIC value.

cleaned_model <- glm(weight ~ age + sex + mean_NAO + year + site + year:mean_NAO,
                     data = cleaned_data)
par (mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(cleaned_model)

check_model(cleaned_model)

cleaned_model2 <- glm(weight ~ age + sex + site + age:sex,
                      data = cleaned_data)
plot(cleaned_model2)

check_model(cleaned_model2)


We should compare this data to a gamma distributed GLM, as our histogram was right-skewed.

gamma_model <- glm(weight ~ age 
                   + sex 
                   + mean_NAO 
                   + year 
                   + site 
                   + year:mean_NAO,
                     data = cleaned_data,
                   family = Gamma(link ="log"))
par(mfrow = c(2,2))
plot(gamma_model)

lrtest(gamma_model,cleaned_model) #H0: both models fit the data as well as each other
## Likelihood ratio test
## 
## Model 1: weight ~ age + sex + mean_NAO + year + site + year:mean_NAO
## Model 2: weight ~ age + sex + mean_NAO + year + site + year:mean_NAO
##   #Df  LogLik Df  Chisq Pr(>Chisq)    
## 1   8 -3032.1                         
## 2   8 -2660.2  0 743.88  < 2.2e-16 ***
## ---
## Signif. codes:  0 '***' 0.001 '**' 0.01 '*' 0.05 '.' 0.1 ' ' 1
AIC(cleaned_model)
## [1] 5336.354
AIC(cleaned_model2)
## [1] 5709.373


Comparing the gamma and Gaussian distributed GLMs, the Gaussian residuals have a far better distribution, QQ plot and lower AIC value. The p-value given by our likelihood-ratio test determines that our gaussian distribution fits significantly better than our gamma distribution.

We can run an ANOVA with all these models to determine which is the best fit.

glmm_test <- anova(ID_pop_model, glmm_model_pop, glmm_model_ID)
glmm_test
## Data: cleaned_data

The two best models I have fitted are not statistically significant from each other. As site does not effect the fit of the model, for simplicity of the model we may not include site as a predictor.

If the values predicted by the model are similar to that observed by the data, we can assume our model is a good fit.

predicted_values <- predict(ID_pop_nosite, type = "response") #create prediction

#add predicted and observed data into a separate dataframe

                       "observed" = cleaned_data$weight)

Our data fits strongly against the x=y line, suggesting our model is emulating the values well.

#turn into a dataframe so i can merge with the tidy model
confints_data <- data.frame(
  term = c("(Intercept)", "age", "sexm", "year", "mean_NAO", "year:mean_NAO", "Std.Dev.(Intercept)|ID", "Std.Dev.(Intercept)|pop_size"),
  conf_low = c(-4.00682549, 0.50064248, 0.29484692, -0.01095479, -63.32640952, 0.01485751, 0.57697774, 0.13662049),
  conf_high = c(26.305624431, 0.512871652, 0.549344346, 0.004240989, -28.925979182, 0.032003689, 0.669119454, 0.241118326),
  estimate = c(11.1493995, 0.5067571, 0.4220956, -0.0033569, -46.1261944, 0.0234306, 0.6213429, 0.1814985)
)

tidied_model <- broom.mixed::tidy(ID_pop_nosite, conf.int = FALSE) %>%
  mutate(term = ifelse(grepl("sd__(Int", term, fixed = TRUE),
                       paste(group, term, sep = "."),
                       term))

#merge the tidy data frame with confidence intervals based on 'term'
tidy_merge <- merge(tidied_model, confints_data, by = "term")
tidy_merge

sorted_tidied_model_data <- 
  tidy_merge %>%
  filter(effect=="fixed") %>%
  filter(term!="(Intercept)") %>%
  mutate(term=factor(term, levels = rev(term)))

#plot error bars of  estimated coefficients
ggplot(sorted_tidied_model_data, aes(x=estimate.x, y=term)) + 
  geom_errorbar(aes(xmin=conf_low, xmax=conf_high),                       
                width=0.3, 
                col="grey50",
                alpha=0.7) +
  geom_point(col="lightpink", size=5, alpha=0.9) +

  ylab("") +
  xlab("Coefficient estimate") +

       caption = "year and year:mean_NAO seem to have little effect.
       However, interaction in significance testing previous 
       suggested significance of year_mean_NAO,
       and model fitting testing suggested that
       this interaction has a positive effect 
       on the model. Previously aware of little
       effect of year itself.")

Conclusion

Comparing our model to our observed values, the model follows the positive trend of the data. The error testing undertaken determined the residuals of the data were normally distributed; our descriptive statistics suggest the selected model was the best fit.

Overall, age, sex, NAO were all significant effectors of Soay sheep weight.
